text: Lars, before you think about opening up the carburetor, try adjusting the fuel idle mixture. I've found that the "idle circuit" of a carburetor also controls your low-speed fuel mixture, up to about 2,000 rpm. text:
Intimacy on steroids!

Kim, you really put a smile on my face today, a day when I really needed a smile due to all the tears I've been crying today, the day before Resurrection Sunday 2020.

After hearing about the latest death toll in Italy from the COVID-19 virus on CNN this morning, 20,000 people, with the United States trailing just behind them at 18,000 dead as of Good Friday, I just broke down. But your steroids comment helped to put a smile on my face again, at least for just a moment. I'm still pretty sad right now though. Hopefully, I'll be in better spirits tomorrow as I celebrate the resurrection our wonderful Savior and Lord, Jesus Christ.

The reason for my post, however, is to ask you a question about memorizing Psalm 139. I could really use some godly counsel from you if you have a moment to spare. I'm not even sure if you'll see this post since your video is over six years old, but I'm gonna take a chance and ask you my question anyway.

Last year, I also memorized Psalm 139, but only the first eighteen verses. I am so glad I memorized it and had been wanting do so for a very long time and, like you, I wanted to be able to have it with me all the time. My question is a three part question and hopefully, you can answer.

1. When you committed Psalm 139 to memory, did you memorize the entire Psalm, including the uncomfortable parts, verses 19-22?

2. If so, was it difficult for you to bring yourself to memorizing those uncomfortable verses? By difficult, I mean emotionally.

3. If so, how did you do it and how can I bring myself to memorizing those uncomfortable verses?

Thanks Kim! I enjoy your videos. You are such a godly encouragement to me.

Happy Resurrection Day! He is risen!

Your sister in Christ. ğŸ˜Š

text:
Just to share my experience.

I bricked my board with the windows update utility (as usual I guess).
To fix it I used an old ECS G31-M7 (v1.0) board. It doesn't have a LPT port but it has an LPT header. I searched for the pins layout and once I've found it i simply connected them with the SPI header of the ASUS P5B. I didn't use any resistors and capacitors. The power supply I have outputs 3.3V at the orange cables of the SATA connectors so I used it for the SPI power. It is good to use the same supply for the SPI connector, that you use on the programming PC due to ground differences. Otherwise you will have to connect one black cable of the supply (you can use one on the SATA port that you took the orange cable from) wich I did just to make sure.

I connected the SPI cable before booting just to make sure that the both boards start at the same time. This is neccessary in my oppinion just because of the SPI specifications.

I booted up my FreeDOS USB drive on wich I have also set a folder with the neccessary files - SPIPGM2 and the bios for the update. I used the last version of the bios because it doesn't really matter what was the previous one.

I erased the chip, programmed it with /p (doesn't matter if /s or /p in my case) and after that I dumped the chip data to the USB drive.

I rebooted with Windows just to check if the dumped data matches the one in the bios rom file. They should be absolutely exact. This will save you time if you have to remount the board to a PC in order to check if it's working.

Afterwards I cleared the CMOS, put the board in place and booted up. I had no problems with anything and the overal time I have spend was 30min's for the reflash procedure and 30min's to solder an LPT cable I didn't even used and maybe 2-3hrs of searching for the info of how to do this.

So overall I'm really happy how it turned out, I'm currently using the board and I have no problems. I ran an ASUS procedure just to verify the BIOS integrity and it was a 100% match.

Thanks for the guide.

Thank you for showing how it comes apart.

Went to use my mains version this morning and found the boss that connects this linkage to the front wheels had gone missing. 
Of course the part is no longer available - a sure sign that it's a known failure point. 
It's still usable but it looks like I'll be fabricating a replacement boss.
[Later] Got it apart after dealing with a ruined head on a screw. The boss was stuck inside a cavity in the wheel housing which makes things a lot easier as it's now just a metal plate to fix it back on the linkage.
